Understanding this in JavaScript
💡 What this Represents

👉 this refers to the object that is calling the function

Think of it as:
“Who is calling me right now?”

🌍 this in Global Context
console.log(this);
👉 In browsers:
this → window object
👉 In Node.js:
this → {} (module.exports)

📦 this Inside Objects
const user = {
    name: "Rahul",
    greet: function () {
        console.log(this.name);
    }
};

user.greet();

Output - Rahul

⚙️ this Inside Functions
function show() {
    console.log(this);
}

show();

👉 In non-strict mode:
this → global object (window)
👉 In strict mode:
"use strict";
function show() {
    console.log(this);
}
show();
this → undefined

🔄 How Calling Context Changes this
🧠 Key Rule:
👉 this depends on HOW a function is called, not where it is written

Example 1: Same Function, Different Caller
const person1 = {
    name: "Amit",
    greet: function () {
        console.log(this.name);
    }
};

const person2 = {
    name: "Neha"
};

person2.greet = person1.greet;

person1.greet(); // Amit
person2.greet(); // Neha

👉 The function is the same
👉 But this changes based on the caller

🔹 Example 2: Losing Context
const user = {
    name: "Rahul",
    greet: function () {
        console.log(this.name);
    }
};
const fn = user.greet;
fn();

🔹 Example 2: Losing Context
const user = {
    name: "Rahul",
    greet: function () {
        console.log(this.name);
    }
};

const fn = user.greet;
fn();
❌ Output:
undefined

👉 Why?

Function is called without an object
So this becomes global (or undefined in strict mode)


| Scenario                          | Value of `this`    |
| --------------------------------- | ------------------ |
| Global scope                      | `window` (browser) |
| Object method                     | The object itself  |
| Regular function                  | Global / undefined |
| Method assigned to another object | New object         |

⚖️ Quick Comparison
✅ Object Method
obj.method(); // this = obj
❌ Standalone Function
method(); // this = window / undefined

🎯 Key Takeaways
this = who is calling the function
It is determined at call time, not definition time
Inside objects → this refers to the object
In normal functions → global or undefined
Changing the caller changes this
